    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Literally "Chinese floral motifs" or "Chinese flower designs", this pattern characteristically merges intricate floral motifs into geometric, frequently circular or diamond-shaped, designs. It was introduced to China from Japan as early as the Nara period (710-794) and is sometimes used interchangeably with "karakusa", meaning "Chinese grass motif".</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000047828/JAANUS [online] (2001-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000050006/Hays, Nō Costumes and Other Japanese Costumes of the Art Institute of Chicago, Art Institute of Chicago Museum Studies (1992)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000050004/Moran, Kichijōten, a Painting of the Nara Period, Artibus Asiae (1962)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>De naam van dit patroon betekent letterlijk 'Chinese bloemmotieven' of 'Chinese bloemontwerpen' en heeft als kenmerk dat het ingewikkelde bloemmotieven combineert tot geometrische, vaak ronde of ruitvormige ontwerpen. Het kwam al in de Nara-periode (710-794) via Japan in China terecht en wordt soms gebruikt als synoniem van 'karakusa', wat 'Chinees grasmotief' betekent.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000113770/AAT-Ned (1994-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>字面上之意義為「中國花紋圖案」或「中國花紋設計圖樣」，此一圖案典型地將錯綜複雜的花紋，合併組織成通常是圓環形狀或鑽石形狀的幾何設計圖樣。它早在西元七一○至七九四年間的奈良時代就由日本引進中國，而且有時會和意義為「中國草紋圖案」的「唐草」(Karakusa)圖飾交互使用。</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000250/AS-Academia Sinica</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
